# %load http://matplotlib.org/plot_directive/mpl_examples/mplot3d/contour3d_demo.py
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import axes3d
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

fig = plt.figure()
ax = fig.add_subplot(111, projection='3d')
X, Y, Z = axes3d.get_test_data(0.05)
cset = ax.contour(X, Y, Z)
ax.clabel(cset, fontsize=9, inline=1)

plt.show()

Let's go with some plotting now, to see whether it works inline.

import numpy
import scipy

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from scipy.special import jn

x=numpy.linspace(0,4*numpy.pi)

for i in range(0,4):
    plt.plot(x,jn(i,x))

print("Done!")
In the above example, nothing gets plotted because nothing is shown. Now, the magic happens. After the command below has been input, all code produces inline figures.

A good way to show how the interactive version of iPython works is to let students play with the matplotlib inline command. Delete it, run the plot - nothing is shown. Add it, but don't run the cell, just run the cell with the plot - nada. Run the matplotlib cell, run the plot - Bingo.
